  <h2 id="compounds">Essential N3 Compound Words (熟語)</h2>
  <p>Kanji rarely appear alone — they form compound words (熟語 jukugo) that are the real building blocks of intermediate Japanese vocabulary:</p>

  <table style="width:100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
    <thead>
      <tr style="background: #dc2626; color: white;">
        <th style="padding: 10px; text-align: left;">Compound</th>
        <th style="padding: 10px; text-align: left;">Reading</th>
        <th style="padding: 10px; text-align: left;">Meaning</th>
        <th style="padding: 10px; text-align: left;">Component Logic</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr style="background: #f8fafc;"><td style="padding: 10px;">経験</td><td style="padding: 10px;">けいけん</td><td style="padding: 10px;">experience</td><td style="padding: 10px;">pass through + test = experience</td></tr>
      <tr style="background: #ffffff;"><td style="padding: 10px;">確認</td><td style="padding: 10px;">かくにん</td><td style="padding: 10px;">confirmation</td><td style="padding: 10px;">certain + recognize = confirm</td></tr>
      <tr style="background: #f8fafc;"><td style="padding: 10px;">判断</td><td style="padding: 10px;">はんだん</td><td style="padding: 10px;">judgment</td><td style="padding: 10px;">judge + cut = judgment</td></tr>
      <tr style="background: #ffffff;"><td style="padding: 10px;">連絡</td><td style="padding: 10px;">れんらく</td><td style="padding: 10px;">contact</td><td style="padding: 10px;">connect + link = contact</td></tr>
      <tr style="background: #f8fafc;"><td style="padding: 10px;">準備</td><td style="padding: 10px;">じゅんび</td><td style="padding: 10px;">preparation</td><td style="padding: 10px;">standard + prepare = preparation</td></tr>
      <tr style="background: #ffffff;"><td style="padding: 10px;">関係</td><td style="padding: 10px;">かんけい</td><td style="padding: 10px;">relationship</td><td style="padding: 10px;">barrier + connect = relationship</td></tr>
      <tr style="background: #f8fafc;"><td style="padding: 10px;">参加</td><td style="padding: 10px;">さんか</td><td style="padding: 10px;">participation</td><td style="padding: 10px;">join + add = participate</td></tr>
      <tr style="background: #ffffff;"><td style="padding: 10px;">相談</td><td style="padding: 10px;">そうだん</td><td style="padding: 10px;">consultation</td><td style="padding: 10px;">mutual + talk = consult</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2 id="similar-kanji">Easily Confused Kanji Pairs</h2>
  <p>These N3 kanji look similar but have different meanings. The test loves these:</p>

  <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(280px, 1fr)); gap: 1rem; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
    <div style="background: #fef2f2; border: 1px solid #fca5a5; padding: 1rem; border-radius: 8px;">
      <strong>待 vs 持</strong>
      <p style="font-size: 0.9rem;">待つ (まつ) = wait ↔ 持つ (もつ) = hold/carry</p>
      <p style="font-size: 0.85rem; color: #666;">Tip: 待 has the "go" radical (彳) = wait to go. 持 has the "hand" radical (扌) = hold in hand.</p>
    </div>
    <div style="background: #fef2f2; border: 1px solid #fca5a5; padding: 1rem; border-radius: 8px;">
      <strong>届 vs 届</strong>
      <p style="font-size: 0.9rem;">届ける (とどける) = deliver ↔ 届く (とどく) = arrive/reach</p>
      <p style="font-size: 0.85rem; color: #666;">Same kanji but transitive vs intransitive! ける = you deliver, く = it reaches.</p>
    </div>
    <div style="background: #fef2f2; border: 1px solid #fca5a5; padding: 1rem; border-radius: 8px;">
      <strong>決 vs 泣</strong>
      <p style="font-size: 0.9rem;">決める (きめる) = decide ↔ 泣く (なく) = cry</p>
      <p style="font-size: 0.85rem; color: #666;">Both have the water radical (氵) but different right sides. 決 has 夬, 泣 has 立.</p>
    </div>
    <div style="background: #fef2f2; border: 1px solid #fca5a5; padding: 1rem; border-radius: 8px;">
      <strong>増 vs 贈</strong>
      <p style="font-size: 0.9rem;">増える (ふえる) = increase ↔ 贈る (おくる) = give a gift</p>
      <p style="font-size: 0.85rem; color: #666;">増 has 土 (earth/stack up). 贈 has 貝 (shell/money = gift).</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2 id="study-method">The Most Effective N3 Kanji Study Method</h2>

  <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(250px, 1fr)); gap: 1rem; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
    <div style="background: #f0f9ff; border: 2px solid #3b82f6; padding: 1.2rem; border-radius: 8px;">
      <strong style="color: #2563eb;">1. Learn in Word Pairs</strong>
      <p style="font-size: 0.9rem; margin: 0.5rem 0 0;">Never learn a kanji alone. Always learn it with 2–3 compound words. For 経: learn 経験 (experience), 経済 (economy), 経由 (via).</p>
    </div>
    <div style="background: #f0fdf4; border: 2px solid #22c55e; padding: 1.2rem; border-radius: 8px;">
      <strong style="color: #16a34a;">2. Radical Decomposition</strong>
      <p style="font-size: 0.9rem; margin: 0.5rem 0 0;">Break kanji into radicals. Use our <a href="/japanese/tools/kanji-lookup/">Kanji Lookup</a> to see component breakdowns. Radicals help you guess meaning and remember structure.</p>
    </div>
    <div style="background: #fefce8; border: 2px solid #eab308; padding: 1.2rem; border-radius: 8px;">
      <strong style="color: #ca8a04;">3. Spaced Repetition</strong>
      <p style="font-size: 0.9rem; margin: 0.5rem 0 0;">Use Anki or WaniKani with the N3 kanji deck. Review daily — even 10 minutes maintains your progress and prevents forgetting.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

